issues.title: new technique for bypassing user-agent restriction
issues.body: Using exit at the end will bypass the necessity of User-agent real data existence, and it worked for several HTB challenges

comments_data.body: Huh? what "user-agent restriction" are you talking about?

hi, i was doing some CTF in HTB and PA and as I pasted payload in User-agent filed in HTTP header and remove the rest it didn't show any thing , I used exit technique at the end and include the real useragent data in the rest and easily gotten the flag : I wanted to write it somewhere if any time, may it works in CTF its POC,

I think the `exit` is only here to terminate the PHP execution and avoid executing other payloads stored in the Apache logs. It doesn't bypass anything related to User-Agent 😉  (https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.exit.php).

> I think the `exit` is only here to terminate the PHP execution and avoid executing other payloads stored in the Apache logs. It doesn't bypass anything related to User-Agent 😉  (https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.exit.php).

Yes it seems correct but i got solved some challenges with it so i felt it might be useful for others and make your payload list more complete
Any way .. thanks for your attention
And good luck ;)

It's funny because no one is wrong in this case, but has to add the "exit" to all other payloads, not only the User-Agent.
Is probably better to do a writeup about the CTF challenge and widely explain that it needed the `exit;`

> Seems interesting but more evidence and testing is needed because not all setups by default are vulnerable to this method!

Hi again thanks for revewing, once i was in a challnge i tested all of lfi payload in repo and couldnt solve it, after research and testing i found this little word and helped me to solve challnge so i thought it might be usefull for others , it just makes the payload list more complete and in situations where time is not enough like CTf it will be beneficial

issues.title: CORS and CRLF documentation updated
issues.body: I did a bit of research on CORS and CRLF and thought I'd update the documentation in this repo. If you have further questions regarding the content feel free to ask me.

comments_data.body: Thanks, why did you remove the `Prerequisites` section in CORS, did I miss something ? :)
No, not really, but it seemed a bit confusing to me that these burp settings were titled `prerequisites`, as they are not mandatory for detecting the vulnerability.
They are not mandatory for detecting, but required for the exploitation

Maybe I'm misunderstanding you, but why are they mandatory for exploitation? I would say that you generally don't need Burp to exploit this vulnerability. You simply have to host the PoC under the domain the server accepts and can thus exploit a CSRF vulnerability or leak data across origin boundaries.

It's not about Burp but about the headers sent and received by the client ;)
The exploitation would only work if the client can send an evil "origin" which would be reflected in `the Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header from the server, you also need the header  `Access-Control-Allow-Credential: true` from the server

This picture from PortSwigger explains it better than me : 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12152583/97111105-3f44f780-16dd-11eb-85e3-074392e95f45.png)

Ok then I misunderstood this section. Sorry... 
I originally thought it had something to do with burp.

Do you have a custom pattern that you are using and if so would you mind sharing?

Also `waybackurls target.com >> tee urls.txt` should be `waybackurls target.com | tee urls.txt`

here is all Gf Patterns https://github.com/1ndianl33t/Gf-Patterns

if you already have urls.txt  this will append new urls in the last of  urls.txt ```target.com >> tee urls.txt``` . 
but this will create a new urls.txt  ```waybackurls target.com | tee urls.txt```

OR
```waybackurls target.com >> urls.txt```

issues.title: Add missing link and add ReverseSSH to Reverse Shell Cheatsheet

comments_data.body:
Hi Swissky,

first of all thank you for maintaining this awesome repository!

To provide a little context to this PR:

`ReverseSSH` is a statically linked ssh server that I wrote and extensively used while preparing for the OSCP exam, because I was fed up with the hard-to-handle and often kinda unstable reverse shells.
While I was mostly content with metasploit's multi-handler and catching basic netcat reverse shells, ReverseSSH also brings file transfers via sftp and dynamic port forwarding to the table; all of that in a single binary with less than 1.5MB.

I'm deeply convinced that it also helps others with easily gaining full tty access to target machines once you have a foothold and can drop/execute files, which greatly streamlines local privilege escalation on both linux and windows targets.

In case you have any questions or in case I should provide more information, please let me know!
@swisskyrepo will this be merged?
Nope, the reverse shell cheatsheet is based on tools and languages which can be found on the targeted machine such as Python reverse shell or the `netcat` binary.

Thanks @PinkDev1 for asking and bringing certainty to this MR.

@swisskyrepo I understand your approach with basing the cheat sheet mainly on tools and languages already present on the target machine.
Nonetheless, I see ReverseSSH similar to the [Meterpreter section](https://github.com/swisskyrepo/PayloadsAllTheThings/blob/master/Methodology%20and%20Resources/Reverse%20Shell%20Cheatsheet.md#meterpreter-shell) which also relies on dropping extra files on the target.

In any case, I respect your decision.
You still might want to cherry pick commit [580664174e2edee37c8b847a747d2f24](https://github.com/swisskyrepo/PayloadsAllTheThings/pull/396/commits/2df7a6f8eebd759e89851bddc44553989fa89cc1) which only adds a link to the otherwise easily missed section at the very bottom of the cheat sheet.

Best regards!

issues.title: Use print() function in both Python 2 and Python 3
issues.body:
Legacy __print__ statements are syntax errors in Python 3 but __print()__ function works as expected in both Python 2 and Python 3.

Also: Old style exceptions --> new style for Python 3
* Old style exceptions are syntax errors in Python 3 but new style exceptions work as expected in both Python 2 and Python 3.

comments_data.body:
Hi,
Have you tested the Python3 exploits to check if they are still working ?
By changing raw_input to input some of them are not compatible in both Python 2 and Python 3.

Python 2 behavior for `input`
```python
>>> a = input(">")
>1+1
>>> a
2
```

Python 3 behavior for `input`
```python
>>> a = input(">")
>1+1
>>> a
'1+1'
```

It also seems the EICAR file was detected and deleted by your antivirus ;)
Did you forget the line `from builtins import input`
